<Author>thmilin
<Content>Bearable, but barely. The main issues were cleanliness and functionality on top of the quaint hotel experience. I can take two average beds with a busted vanity chair, tight space, little storage, basic television service, and limited amenities - if everything's clean and on the up and up. When we arrived we got a very pleasant desk clerk working by her lonesome. We got in the room and were satisfied we paid a generally bargain price for what wouldn't be extra service but would do.My friend pulled out the vanity chair and discovered all the framework to support the legs were broken and hanging off of the chair. I opened the closet to discover the iron holder on the closet wall was broken and hanging off. The safe won't hold anything bigger than wallet/purse/passport/jewelry, and there was a really gross stain high on the wall above the closet. There were few plugs for charging cell phones, etc. We turned on all the lights and felt like we were in candlelight. Nice but hard to see.But the windows are very tall, there's crown molding, the decor was battered 18th century elegance and was cute enough. The bathroom looked great ... until further inspection.The floors had been cleaned but not as thoroughly as they could have been - like they'd been mopped but passed over so that soap residue still remained. There was some liquid at the foot of the toilet my friend covered with a towel before she'd use the toilet. I asked and received a shower chair from our very pleasant desk clerk - I had broken my foot - and was thrilled that she brought it up right away. However, the chair was disgusting and nothing you'd ever dare put your tush on. We pulled back the shower curtain and discovered a stained, soiled, battered, unpleasant, scary tub we would never dream of standing barefoot in.I went to wash my hands at the sink and discovered the two pulls worked in opposite nonstandard directions. This sounds weird, but test it on your hotel and home sinks - all pulls work a certain standard way. This one had one pull inverted. Doesn't prevent you from getting water but if you don't test it the opposite way you'd think it was broken.The pedestal base of the sink was grimy and the caulking was peeling away, so it was looking grody. Bearable - until, on turning the water faucet, the entire right side of the sink pulled away from the wall. The sink was basically not sturdily/permanently fixed in place and using the right-hand faucet displaced the whole thing from the wall. Not a huge amount, no, but come on. At this point, all your quaint details like tall french windows and a romantic pedestal sink are lost on me with the nasty tub and gimpy sink.It was late night and we realized there were not enough towels for 2 people. We called down and got a guy, who didn't seem particularly thrilled to get my call and might have been entirely sarcastic when he said Sure, when I asked for extra towels.Two hours later, no towels. I didn't bother calling down again.While we sat enjoying ourselves with some snacks watching the dark, old, small, non hotel-system tv (ie it's basic cable with nothing fancy like movies, etc.) a bug of some sort - we told ourselves it was NOT a roach, we just said it was a bug so we could sleep - crawled around on the nightstand and conquered our little bag of chips.We thought everything would look better in the morning and we'd persevere, since honestly the room just reminded us of San Francisco - a little grimy, but well meaning and well priced.But by the clear, unforgiving light of day that bathroom was just not looking doable. Add to that the required internet and service fees people mention and ... just too much going on to make it worthwhile.Next day, we checked out and headed for a chain hotel. Yes, sacrilege in a place like NOLA, but at this point reliable. Clean, sturdy, good repair rooms are a requirement, not a bonus, for ANY hotel. 
