<Content>A mostly good experience... My wife and I ventured back to New Orleans last week for the French Quarter Festival, our first visit since the hurricane. As usual, I agree with most of the findings I read on Tripadvisor prior to our trip. The Pelham is a nice, clean, historic hotel definitely worthy of consideration, but it is obviously in a struggle against the rest of the city, pertaining to construction sounds, night police sirens, etc. The staff was very helpful, right from the beginning - to include switching us to a room with a window after we had viewed our first room. The parking situation is not good - avoid the thug in the outdoor lot across the street (the rate went from $20 daily to $40, once he thought I was committed. I fortunately found free curbside parking nearby). I witnessed a terrible situation with The Pelham's valet parking. Three young people dressed for a wedding attendance had waited the better part of an hour to still not have their car delivered - and claimed they had missed the wedding. Bottom line - their valet parking is probably not really valet parking, but rather the car being sent to a long term garage elsewhere. And don't venture out late at night (a true statement nowadays for that city in general). The hotel itself was wonderful, but the sounds and loud voices from midnight crime in the street made us happy to be sleeping on the third floor ,and was a reminder that we were again in New Orleans. 
