<Author>omarandjoey
<Content>Make your room request specific at the Pelham. Okay Hotel. Read this... Okay folks. I used Tripadvisor to check my travel arrangements. I looked at all the feedback for the Pelham; and, I called the hotel in advance to see if specific problems had been solved/repaired. Here's the skinny...The hotel is a pretty hotel in the lobby, no doubt. Saddly, the building across the street isn't; and, that's not the Pelham's fault. Be aware, if you are on the front side of the building, You will be woken by the city garbage trucks at or about 3:30 a.m. on or about Wednesday, for exactly or about 20 minutes. We booked a non-smoking, king room. At check-in, we were given room 408 (The clerk was aces all the way around...she was the best).Well here's the problem with room 408: the room had been smoked heavily in; the glass covering the furniture, end tables and such, was dirty; the carpet in the doorways had been torn and the sub floor was exposed; there was a silver dollar size spot of bubble gum (black in color) ground-into the carpet; the bed frame rails are held together by screws, of which the sharp ends are sticking out of the wood (cut my leg sitting on the bed for the first time but it's ok my partner is a doctor); there was a 3 foot grounding wire hanging out of the light fixture in the middle of the room; the bathroom sink was burned all round from cigarettes; the toilet seat was burned with a cigarette (I'm not sure how this happens???What are they smoking with?). Anywho, we made a complaint and we were quickly moved to room 217. Room 217 is the room you see on the internet photo, granted some time ago. It has a nosmoking sign on the door, something 408 does not. The room was okay, it didn't smell of cigarettes; however, there were some cigarette butts on the floor between the headboard and the wall. The decorative pillows on the bed had a variety of stains of which I didn't desire to know more. Someone's feet had been made to rest on the walls around the bed at matress level leaving an unmistakable stripe around the room. The bathroom was marble; however, there was an issue with the cigarette burns in the sink as well and dirt and mold were along the corners of the tub/shower, floor and grout lines. The floor was not mopped, nor was the mirror cleaned for two days.All in all not a bad room for New Orleans. Here's where their customer satisfaction policy kicked in full force!!! Fortunately, the corporate offices for the Pellam, St James, Le Cirque, Astor Crowne Plaza, Parc St. Charles, Lafayette, Chateau Dupre, Holiday Inn Express, Cotton Exchange, and Historic French Market Inn (all the same company) is located 1/2 block away at 517 Magazine. So I walked over, went to the 4th floor and explained to the CEO's office that I would like to clean my own room and meet the houskeeping lady so as to do. I told him that I didn't want my money back. We were not really upset and that we just wanted to stay as long as we could make the room cleaner. They were ever so wonderful. They offered to move us again, to the St. James, and give us another 2 day vacation to the city at their cost, in any deluxe accommodation of our choosing. So, all in all not a bad deal. Now, you want to see a GREAT review, see what I write at the St. James.As for the Pelham, it's an okay hotel. If you're not like me just this side shy of O.C.D. and you don't mind a little wear and tear, the Pelham is the one for you. Perfect for a prom party I'm sure! Oh yea, the parking is 20 dollars a day. 
