<Author>A TripAdvisor Member
<Content>Feel Welcome in New Orleans I would definitely stay here again. I came to New Orleans for a conference that was at the Marriott Hotel (too expensive for me) so I looked on hotels.com and found the Pelham, close by, much cheaper. I arrived on a Saturday night. Just a point...I am not a night person, I like mornings, I am pretty quiet (although I like talking) and I was on my own. So, when I showed up, I was hungry, tired, and lonely. PLUS, I was given what is called an interior room which is a room with no windows...great for college students on a bender who don't want to see the sun all day, but not so great for myself. So, this, coupled with the fact that the wireless internet in my room did not work, (low signal), started to depress me and I really thought I was going to move. HOWEVER, on the advice of the front desk worker at the time, I came down to the lobby and used the internet there...that turned out to be a REALLY REALLY good idea.Let's be fair. This is New Orleans...what are you really coming for? And what was the original purpose of the 'hotel' concept throughout history? HOSPITALITY. And that is PRECISELY what I got when I came down that night. I can use names, because I think the staff will be there for a while. There is a woman who works front desk named Ixtel who absolutely charming and takes a personal satisfaction in the well-being and happiness of all her guests, and a genuine regret when things don't exactly go right. I actually got to observe this firsthand, as I was on the internet a lot and thus sat in the lobby for hours on end, working. ....so I got to see her warm and professional interaction with everyone that came through here. She is the reason that I did not change my reservation to another place that first night. This is what a small hotel should be...a warm, caring staff who want to take care of you! There are others as well: Lakeisha works front desk, and changed my room Sunday morning to a better one, after all the benders checked out. She was extremely welcoming, professional, and gave me pizza. Tim (bellhop) is a very calm and mature young man, and always willing to help, but never pushy. Everyone is willing to offer recommendations of places to go, or perhaps just sit and chat and ask you where you are from.Who would not want to stay here?I suppose if you want an ultra-clean hotel, or you simply are looking for a place to crash, or like hi-rises or whatever, then sure go check somewhere else out. But I have to say I'll stay there again. I don't care that it's next to a soup kitchen. Plus, I think it's getting better. 
